{
  "text": "BLA lesions and b-adrenergic receptor blockade in the BLA prevent the memory-enhancing effects of microinjections of GC receptor agonists into the dorsal hippocampus [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Similarly, BLA inactivation prevents the enhancement of memory consolidation produced by histone deacetylase inhibition in the dorsal hippocampus [CITATION_3] . As noted earlier, recording studies suggest that BLA activity becomes increasingly coupled with activity in downstream brain regions, including the entorhinal cortex, during training, and, moreover, that the increased coupling is related to the degree of learning [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . As findings indicate that BLA inactivation prevents learning-induced changes in ventral hippocampal plasticity [CITATION_6] , the interactions between the BLA and the hippocampus that influence memory consolidation most likely involve BLA influences on plasticity within the hippocampus. This issue is discussed further below.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "26960328",
    "[CITATION_2]": "31339287",
